value: Made for Sir Edward Littleton, Bart., for his new house, Teddesley Park, Staffordshire, 1760; it remained there until removed to London by Lord Hatherton, a collateral descendant, in 1931; exhibited at Messrs Spink's, London and bought through them from Lord Hatherton, 1932.

Terracotta. The sitter's head is turned to the front, held a little forward and looking slightly right. His hair curls at the nape of the neck, he is clean-shaven. His throat is bare, shirt open and the waist-coat is unbuttoned. The shoulders are draped in a cloak.

summary_title: Seeing Pope as Rysbrack saw him
notes: Publ. Illustrated with the marble, p. 24

summary_title: The Art of John Michael Rysbrack in Terracotta

notes: Ref. see pp. 77-8, 223; letter from Rysbrack to Sir Edward Littleton, 11th December 1759. 'As for the bust of Mr Pope you must instruct me how to Dress it, because he is not in that ancient Dress which the others are, neither has he that character in his face. Tho'as great a man.'
